      <div type="section" xml:id="preface">
        <head>Preface</head>
        <!-- <p>General introductory remarks about the edition.</p> -->
        <p> C.4 q.2-3 d.p.c.3 quotes a cryptic statement, not found in Clavis
        Canonum, attributed to St. Brice (†.444), a controversial disciple of
        St. Martin, and his successor as bishop of Tours. ["It is remarkable
        that in his dicta Gratian refers to sources that are not cited in the
        Decretum. Many biblical citations, for example, are found only in the
        dicta. They are often tied to important theological reflections ..."
        Landau, "Gratian and the Decretum Gratiani", 41.]</p>
        <!-- Admont (Aa) -->
        <p>There are two marginal glosses in the Admont (Aa) text of C.4 that
        refer to Burchard's Decretum: "B.xvi. Nemo ſimul ſit." (Burchard 16.15)
        at 4.4.1, and "B.i. Qͥſqͥs." (Burchard 1.160) at 4.6.1. A rubric in
        between C.4 and C.5 ("Explicit liber quintus, incipit liber sextus, de
        episcoporum accusationibus") indicates a non-standard division of the Aa
        ms. into books.</p>
        <!-- Barcelona (Bc) -->
        <p>The order of rubrics in C.4 q.4 is reversed in Bc. The rubric for
        4.4.2 ("Quilibet in causa duas personas gerere non valet") appears
        before 4.4.1, and the rubric for 4.4.1 ("Accusator, testis vel iudex
        aliquis simul esse non potest") appears before 4.4.2. Bc includes two
        canons —  4.6.3 and 4.6.4 — not listed in Winroth's appendix and not
        found in either the Aa or P mss.</p>
        <!-- Paris (P) -->
        <p>The quality of scribal workmanship in the Paris (P) ms. is visibly
        less professional than that in either the Aa or Bc mss.</p>
